{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_8","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' TASK.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Task: goal_leases schema + repository (Phase 3a/3b of goal-level parallelism)\n\nYou are working in an isolated git worktree/branch. Do NOT touch any file\noutside the allowed paths below. Do NOT run `git push`, do NOT merge, do NOT\ntouch `main` or any branch other than the one already checked out here.\n\n## Context\n\nThis backend (FastAPI + SQLAlchemy + Pydantic, `backend/src/` hexagonal\nlayout: domain -> app -> infra & api) is implementing ADR-001's goal-level\nparallelism: different worker PROCESSES will each claim and execute a\ndifferent, independent GOAL of the same long-lived `Plan`, instead of today's\none-worker-owns-the-whole-plan model. This task is ONLY the schema +\nrepository slice — do NOT touch the worker loop, ExecutionHandler, or\nnavigation logic; those land separately.\n\nRead these existing files first to match conventions exactly:\n- `backend/src/infra/db/tables.py` — the existing `plans` table definition,\n  including its lease columns (`claimed_by`, `lease_expires_at`) and the\n  documented \"promoted scalar column\" pattern (search for `paused` — a field\n  maintained on save as a queryable column derived from the JSON blob).\n  Also look at the `execution_runs` table and its partial unique index\n  `uq_execution_runs_active_task` for the sibling-ledger-table pattern this\n  new table should follow (a table that sits BESIDE the `plans` JSON blob,\n  not inside it).\n- `backend/src/infra/db/plan_repository.py` — study `_CLAIM_SQL`,\n  `claim_one_unit`, `heartbeat`, `release` closely. Your new\n  `GoalLeaseRepository`'s claim/heartbeat/release methods must follow the\n  IDENTICAL transactional pattern (indexed `UPDATE ... WHERE claimed_by IS\n  NULL OR lease_expires_at < :now`, checking rowcount to detect a lost race),\n  just scoped to `(plan_id, goal_id)` instead of just `plan_id`.\n- `backend/src/domain/repositories/planner_repo.py` — the existing\n  `PlanRepository` protocol's docstring style; your new\n  `domain/repositories/goal_lease_repo.py` should match this style exactly\n  (Protocol class, one-line-per-method docstrings explaining the contract,\n  not the implementation).\n- `backend/src/app/ports.py` — how domain ports are re-exported here\n  (`AgentEventSink`, `AgentRunner`, etc., all re-exported from\n  `src.domain.ports`) and how `UnitOfWork` in this same file already exposes\n  `plans`, `outbox`, `executions`, `chat` as properties.\n- `backend/src/app/testing/fakes.py` — study `InMemoryPlanRepository`\n  closely, especially its claim/lease dict-based simulation of the SQL\n  claim predicate (it must reproduce the SAME race semantics as the real\n  SQL, just in Python). Your new `InMemoryGoalLeaseRepository` follows the\n  identical shape.\n- `backend/alembic/versions/` — look at the most recent 2-3 migration files\n  (highest-numbered) to match the exact revision-chain header format\n  (`revision`, `down_revision`, `branch_labels`, `depends_on`) and the\n  `op.create_table`/`op.create_index` style already used in this codebase.\n  Your migration's `down_revision` MUST point at the actual current head —\n  run `cd backend && uv run alembic heads` to find it, do not guess.\n\n## What to build\n\n### 1. New alembic migration\nA new table `goal_leases`:\n- `plan_id` (String, FK to `plans.id`, part of composite PK)\n- `goal_id` (String, part of composite PK)\n- `claimed_by` (String, nullable)\n- `claimed_at` (appropriate timestamp/int type matching this codebase's\n  existing convention — check how `plans.lease_expires_at` is typed and\n  match it, don't invent a new convention)\n- `lease_expires_at` (same type as above, nullable)\n- `lease_seconds` (Integer, nullable)\n\nAdd an index on `(claimed_by, lease_expires_at)` for the claim query.\nRows are created lazily (no upfront seeding) — the repository's claim method\ndoes an upsert-like `INSERT OR IGNORE` then a conditional `UPDATE`.\n\n### 2. `backend/src/domain/repositories/goal_lease_repo.py` (new)\nA `GoalLeaseRepository` Protocol with:\n- `claim_one_ready_goal(plan_id: str, goal_id: str, worker_id: str, lease_seconds: int, now: datetime) -> bool`\n  — attempt to claim this SPECIFIC (plan_id, goal_id) pair (the caller has\n  already decided which goal is ready and unclaimed via domain-layer\n  `ready_goal_ids` — this repository method does NOT do any JSON-blob\n  scanning itself, it only does the indexed claim attempt for one already-\n  identified goal). Returns True if claimed, False if lost the race (already\n  claimed and lease not expired).\n- `heartbeat(plan_id: str, goal_id: str, worker_id: str, lease_seconds: int, now: datetime) -> None`\n  — renew an existing live claim; no-op / raise nothing special if the\n  caller no longer holds it (match whatever `PlanRepository.heartbeat`\n  already does for the analogous case — read it and mirror it).\n- `release(plan_id: str, goal_id: str, worker_id: str) -> None` — release\n  only if `worker_id` still matches (matches `PlanRepository.release`'s\n  guard).\n- `is_claim_live(plan_id: str, goal_id: str, now: datetime) -> bool` — read\n  the row and report the fresh boolean without mutating.\n\nDo not include a \"scan all plans for ready goals\" method here — that\norchestration logic (which needs the domain's `ready_goal_ids` +\nreconstructing `Plan` objects) belongs in a use-case that will be added in a\nLATER task, not this repository. Keep this repository a pure claim/heartbeat/\nrelease primitive over one already-identified `(plan_id, goal_id)` pair,\nexactly mirroring `PlanRepository`'s existing shape at the per-goal\ngranularity.\n\n### 3. `backend/src/infra/db/goal_lease_repository.py` (new)\n`SqliteGoalLeaseRepository` implementing the above protocol against a real\nSQLAlchemy `sessionmaker[Session]` (same constructor signature style as\n`SqlitePlanRepository`/other repos in `infra/db/`), using the same\ntransactional UPDATE-with-rowcount-check pattern as `PlanRepository`'s\n`_CLAIM_SQL`/`heartbeat`/`release`.\n\n### 4. `backend/src/app/testing/fakes.py` addition\n`InMemoryGoalLeaseRepository` implementing the same protocol with a plain\nin-process dict keyed by `(plan_id, goal_id)`, reproducing the exact same\nclaim/expiry semantics as the real SQL version (this is what\n`tests/unit/orchestration/`'s dual-backend `env_factory` fixture will use\nfor the `memory` parametrization — it must never diverge from what the real\nSQLite adapter does, since the whole point of the dual-backend test pattern\nis proving both give identical answers).\n\n### 5. Wire `app/ports.py`\nAdd `GoalLeaseRepository` to the re-exports (following the exact pattern\nalready used for the other domain ports re-exported there) and add a\n`goal_leases: GoalLeaseRepository` property to the `UnitOfWork` protocol\nalready defined in that file (look at how `plans`/`outbox`/`executions` are\nalready declared as properties on it — match exactly).\n\n### 6. Wire the real UnitOfWork implementation\nFind wherever the concrete `SqliteUnitOfWork` (implementing `UnitOfWork`)\nconstructs `plans`/`outbox`/`executions` today (`infra/db/unit_of_work.py`\nmost likely) and add the `goal_leases` property there too, constructing\n`SqliteGoalLeaseRepository` the same way the others are constructed.\n\n### 7. Tests\n- `backend/tests/unit/orchestration/test_goal_lease_repository.py` (new):\n  parametrized dual-backend (memory + real sqlite via `tmp_path`, following\n  whatever fixture pattern the existing `PlanRepository` tests already use\n  for this — grep for how other repo tests parametrize memory vs sqlite) —\n  claim succeeds once, a second claim by a different worker_id fails while\n  the lease is live, claim succeeds again after `FakeClock.advance()` past\n  `lease_expires_at`, heartbeat extends the lease, release clears it so a\n  new claim succeeds immediately.\n- A **real-SQLite-only** integration test (mark with whatever this repo's\n  existing `-m integration` convention is) that opens two separate\n  `SqliteGoalLeaseRepository` instances against the SAME on-disk db file and\n  has them race `claim_one_ready_goal` for the identical `(plan_id, goal_id)`\n  concurrently (use `concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor` with 2 workers,\n  or two threads) — assert exactly one succeeds. This is the one test that\n  MUST exercise real sqlite3 row-level contention, not the fake.\n\n## Verification (run in THIS worktree, using its own venv — never assume the\ncoordinator's main working tree state)\n\n```\ncd backend\nuv run alembic upgrade head   # confirm the new migration applies cleanly on top of head\nuv run ruff check src tests --fix\nuv run mypy src\nuv run pytest -m \"not integration\" -q\nuv run pytest -m integration -q\n```\n\nAll of the above MUST pass, mypy MUST report zero errors, before you\nconsider this done. If `mypy` or a test fails, fix it — do not report success\nwith a failing check.\n\n## When done\n\nDelete this TASK.md file, then `git add -A` (excluding nothing you didn't\nintend) and `git commit` your changes with a clear commit message. Do NOT\npush, do NOT merge into any other branch. Report back a summary of exactly\nwhat you created/changed and the full output of the verification commands\nabove.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
